post_cb({"24406000": {"CommentCount": "3", "AcceptedAnswerId": "24406076", "CreationDate": "2014-06-25T10:18:41.150", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-27T15:48:44.043", "PostTypeId": "1", "ViewCount": "358", "FavoriteCount": "0", "Title": "long float c++ visual studio 2013", "Id": "24406000", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>I've started to learn C++ with Stroustrup's C++ programming book - data types. It says that for floating point types language have float, double, long double types. But this program runs good for me:</p>\n<pre><code>long float float2{ 5.0F };\ncout &lt;&lt; float2 &lt;&lt; endl;\n\ncout &lt;&lt; \"size of long float: \" &lt;&lt; sizeof(long float) &lt;&lt; endl; // 8\n\nstd::cout &lt;&lt; \"min long float value: \" &lt;&lt; (long float)std::numeric_limits&lt;long float&gt;::min() &lt;&lt; std::endl; // 2.22507e-308\nstd::cout &lt;&lt; \"max long float value: \" &lt;&lt; (long float)std::numeric_limits&lt;long float&gt;::max() &lt;&lt; std::endl &lt;&lt; std::endl; // 1.79769e+308\n</code></pre>\n<p>i.e. the same as double. So what's the difference? As far as I knew before there's no such type - <strong><em>long float</em></strong>. Is it the microsoft compiler feature? Is it a new standard?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><floating-point>", "OwnerUserId": "1341942", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "28174453": {"ParentId": "24406000", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>You should be carefull using \"long\" because it takes more bytes, like an Integer is 4 bytes, an float is 16 bytes. and not sure if you have to use long for a number like \"5.0f\".</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "3742860", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "28174453", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-01-27T15:48:44.043", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-27T15:48:44.043"}, "24406076": {"ParentId": "24406000", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24406000_24406076_0\">So what's the difference?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><code>double</code> is a standard type; <code>long float</code> is not. For example, GCC rejects it: <a href=\"http://ideone.com/0pIhgK\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://ideone.com/0pIhgK</a>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24406000_24406076_1\">As far as I knew before there's no such type - <code>long float</code>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Not in standard C++, no.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24406000_24406076_2\">Is it the microsoft compiler feature?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Looks like it. That compiler is somewhat notorious for its language \"extensions\". I believe it has an option to disable (at least some of) them; it would be a good idea to do that, if you want to learn portable C++.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24406000_24406076_3\">Is it a new standard?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There's no mention of it in C++11, or the <a href=\"https://isocpp.org/files/papers/N3797.pdf\" rel=\"noreferrer\">latest draft of C++14</a>. The floating point types are specified in 3.9.1/8:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24406000_24406076_4\">There are three <em>\ufb02oating point types</em>: <code>float</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>long double</code>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "204847", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "24406076", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2014-06-25T10:22:31.070", "LastActivityDate": "2014-06-25T10:22:31.070"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_24406000_24406076_4": {"section_id": 7217, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}, "n3337": {"so_24406000_24406076_4": {"section_id": 6961, "quality": 0.8888888888888888, "length": 8}}, "n4659": {"so_24406000_24406076_4": {"section_id": 8726, "quality": 0.7777777777777778, "length": 7}}}});